237 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_SPARSE) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
238 /*************************************************************************
239 Sparse matrix structure.
240 
241 You should use ALGLIB functions to work with sparse matrix. Never try to
242 access its fields directly!
243 
244 NOTES ON THE SPARSE STORAGE FORMATS
245 
246 Sparse matrices can be stored using several formats:
247 * Hash-Table representation
248 * Compressed Row Storage (CRS)
249 * Skyline matrix storage (SKS)
250 
251 Each of the formats has benefits and drawbacks:
252 * Hash-table is good for dynamic operations (insertion of new elements),
253  but does not support linear algebra operations
254 * CRS is good for operations like matrix-vector or matrix-matrix products,
255  but its initialization is less convenient - you have to tell row sizes
256  at the initialization, and you have to fill matrix only row by row,
257  from left to right.
258 * SKS is a special format which is used to store triangular factors from
259  Cholesky factorization. It does not support dynamic modification, and
260  support for linear algebra operations is very limited.
261 
262 Tables below outline information about these two formats:
263 
264  OPERATIONS WITH MATRIX HASH CRS SKS
265  creation + + +
266  SparseGet + + +
267  SparseRewriteExisting + + +
268  SparseSet + + +
269  SparseAdd +
270  SparseGetRow + +
271  SparseGetCompressedRow + +
272  sparse-dense linear algebra + +
273 *************************************************************************/
274 class _sparsematrix_owner
275 {
276 public:
281  _sparsematrix_owner();
287  _sparsematrix_owner(const _sparsematrix_owner &rhs);
294  _sparsematrix_owner& operator=(const _sparsematrix_owner &rhs);
299  virtual ~_sparsematrix_owner();
305  alglib_impl::sparsematrix* c_ptr();
311  alglib_impl::sparsematrix* c_ptr() const;
312 protected:
313  alglib_impl::sparsematrix *p_struct;
314 };

810 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_SPARSE) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
811 /*************************************************************************
812 This function creates sparse matrix in a Hash-Table format.
813 
814 This function creates Hast-Table matrix, which can be converted to CRS
815 format after its initialization is over. Typical usage scenario for a
816 sparse matrix is:
817 1. creation in a Hash-Table format
818 2. insertion of the matrix elements
819 3. conversion to the CRS representation
820 4. matrix is passed to some linear algebra algorithm
821 
822 Some information about different matrix formats can be found below, in
823 the "NOTES" section.
824 
825 INPUT PARAMETERS
826  M - number of rows in a matrix, M>=1
827  N - number of columns in a matrix, N>=1
828  K - K>=0, expected number of non-zero elements in a matrix.
829  K can be inexact approximation, can be less than actual
830  number of elements (table will grow when needed) or
831  even zero).
832  It is important to understand that although hash-table
833  may grow automatically, it is better to provide good
834  estimate of data size.
835 
836 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
837  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table representation.
838  All elements of the matrix are zero.
839 
840 NOTE 1
841 
842 Hash-tables use memory inefficiently, and they have to keep some amount
843 of the "spare memory" in order to have good performance. Hash table for
844 matrix with K non-zero elements will need C*K*(8+2*sizeof(int)) bytes,
845 where C is a small constant, about 1.5-2 in magnitude.
846 
847 CRS storage, from the other side, is more memory-efficient, and needs
848 just K*(8+sizeof(int))+M*sizeof(int) bytes, where M is a number of rows
849 in a matrix.
850 
851 When you convert from the Hash-Table to CRS representation, all unneeded
852 memory will be freed.
853 
854 NOTE 2
855 
856 Comments of SparseMatrix structure outline information about different
857 sparse storage formats. We recommend you to read them before starting to
858 use ALGLIB sparse matrices.
859 
860 NOTE 3
861 
862 This function completely overwrites S with new sparse matrix. Previously
863 allocated storage is NOT reused. If you want to reuse already allocated
864 memory, call SparseCreateBuf function.
865 
866  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
867  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
868 *************************************************************************/
869 void sparsecreate(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t k, sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
870 void sparsecreate(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
871 
872 
873 /*************************************************************************
874 This version of SparseCreate function creates sparse matrix in Hash-Table
875 format, reusing previously allocated storage as much as possible. Read
876 comments for SparseCreate() for more information.
877 
878 INPUT PARAMETERS
879  M - number of rows in a matrix, M>=1
880  N - number of columns in a matrix, N>=1
881  K - K>=0, expected number of non-zero elements in a matrix.
882  K can be inexact approximation, can be less than actual
883  number of elements (table will grow when needed) or
884  even zero).
885  It is important to understand that although hash-table
886  may grow automatically, it is better to provide good
887  estimate of data size.
888  S - SparseMatrix structure which MAY contain some already
889  allocated storage.
890 
891 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
892  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table representation.
893  All elements of the matrix are zero.
894  Previously allocated storage is reused, if its size
895  is compatible with expected number of non-zeros K.
896 
897  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
898  Copyright 14.01.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
899 *************************************************************************/
900 void sparsecreatebuf(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t k, const sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
901 void sparsecreatebuf(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

903 
904 /*************************************************************************
905 This function creates sparse matrix in a CRS format (expert function for
906 situations when you are running out of memory).
907 
908 This function creates CRS matrix. Typical usage scenario for a CRS matrix
909 is:
910 1. creation (you have to tell number of non-zero elements at each row at
911  this moment)
912 2. insertion of the matrix elements (row by row, from left to right)
913 3. matrix is passed to some linear algebra algorithm
914 
915 This function is a memory-efficient alternative to SparseCreate(), but it
916 is more complex because it requires you to know in advance how large your
917 matrix is. Some information about different matrix formats can be found
918 in comments on SparseMatrix structure. We recommend you to read them
919 before starting to use ALGLIB sparse matrices..
920 
921 INPUT PARAMETERS
922  M - number of rows in a matrix, M>=1
923  N - number of columns in a matrix, N>=1
924  NER - number of elements at each row, array[M], NER[I]>=0
925 
926 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
927  S - sparse M*N matrix in CRS representation.
928  You have to fill ALL non-zero elements by calling
929  SparseSet() BEFORE you try to use this matrix.
930 
931 NOTE: this function completely overwrites S with new sparse matrix.
932  Previously allocated storage is NOT reused. If you want to reuse
933  already allocated memory, call SparseCreateCRSBuf function.
934 
935  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
936  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
937 *************************************************************************/
938 void sparsecreatecrs(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const integer_1d_array &ner, sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

948 1. creation (you have to tell number of non-zero elements at each row at
949  this moment)
950 2. insertion of the matrix elements (row by row, from left to right)

953 This function is a memory-efficient alternative to SparseCreate(), but it
954 is more complex because it requires you to know in advance how large your
955 matrix is. Some information about different matrix formats can be found
956 in comments on SparseMatrix structure. We recommend you to read them
957 before starting to use ALGLIB sparse matrices..

959 INPUT PARAMETERS

962  NER - number of elements at each row, array[M], NER[I]>=0

977 /*************************************************************************
978 This function creates sparse matrix in a SKS format (skyline storage
979 format). In most cases you do not need this function - CRS format better
980 suits most use cases.
981 
982 INPUT PARAMETERS
983  M, N - number of rows(M) and columns (N) in a matrix:
984  * M=N (as for now, ALGLIB supports only square SKS)
985  * N>=1
986  * M>=1
987  D - "bottom" bandwidths, array[M], D[I]>=0.
988  I-th element stores number of non-zeros at I-th row,
989  below the diagonal (diagonal itself is not included)
990  U - "top" bandwidths, array[N], U[I]>=0.
991  I-th element stores number of non-zeros at I-th row,
992  above the diagonal (diagonal itself is not included)
993 
994 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
995  S - sparse M*N matrix in SKS representation.
996  All elements are filled by zeros.
997  You may use sparseset() to change their values.
998 
999 NOTE: this function completely overwrites S with new sparse matrix.
1000  Previously allocated storage is NOT reused. If you want to reuse
1001  already allocated memory, call SparseCreateSKSBuf function.
1002 
1003  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1004  Copyright 13.01.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1005 *************************************************************************/
1006 void sparsecreatesks(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const integer_1d_array &d, const integer_1d_array &u, sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1009 /*************************************************************************
1010 This is "buffered" version of SparseCreateSKS() which reuses memory
1011 previously allocated in S (of course, memory is reallocated if needed).
1012 
1013 This function creates sparse matrix in a SKS format (skyline storage
1014 format). In most cases you do not need this function - CRS format better
1015 suits most use cases.
1016 
1017 INPUT PARAMETERS
1018  M, N - number of rows(M) and columns (N) in a matrix:
1019  * M=N (as for now, ALGLIB supports only square SKS)
1020  * N>=1
1021  * M>=1
1022  D - "bottom" bandwidths, array[M], 0<=D[I]<=I.
1023  I-th element stores number of non-zeros at I-th row,
1024  below the diagonal (diagonal itself is not included)
1025  U - "top" bandwidths, array[N], 0<=U[I]<=I.
1026  I-th element stores number of non-zeros at I-th row,
1027  above the diagonal (diagonal itself is not included)
1028 
1029 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1030  S - sparse M*N matrix in SKS representation.
1031  All elements are filled by zeros.
1032  You may use sparseset() to change their values.
1033 
1034  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1035  Copyright 13.01.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1036 *************************************************************************/
1037 void sparsecreatesksbuf(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const integer_1d_array &d, const integer_1d_array &u, const sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1040 /*************************************************************************
1041 This function creates sparse matrix in a SKS format (skyline storage
1042 format). Unlike more general sparsecreatesks(), this function creates
1043 sparse matrix with constant bandwidth.
1044 
1045 You may want to use this function instead of sparsecreatesks() when your
1046 matrix has constant or nearly-constant bandwidth, and you want to
1047 simplify source code.
1048 
1049 INPUT PARAMETERS
1050  M, N - number of rows(M) and columns (N) in a matrix:
1051  * M=N (as for now, ALGLIB supports only square SKS)
1052  * N>=1
1053  * M>=1
1054  BW - matrix bandwidth, BW>=0
1055 
1056 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1057  S - sparse M*N matrix in SKS representation.
1058  All elements are filled by zeros.
1059  You may use sparseset() to change their values.
1060 
1061 NOTE: this function completely overwrites S with new sparse matrix.
1062  Previously allocated storage is NOT reused. If you want to reuse
1063  already allocated memory, call sparsecreatesksbandbuf function.
1064 
1065  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1066  Copyright 25.12.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
1067 *************************************************************************/
1068 void sparsecreatesksband(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t bw, sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1130 void sparseswap(const sparsematrix &s0, const sparsematrix &s1, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1133 /*************************************************************************
1134 This function adds value to S[i,j] - element of the sparse matrix. Matrix
1135 must be in a Hash-Table mode.
1136 
1137 In case S[i,j] already exists in the table, V i added to its value. In
1138 case S[i,j] is non-existent, it is inserted in the table. Table
1139 automatically grows when necessary.
1140 
1141 INPUT PARAMETERS
1142  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table representation.
1143  Exception will be thrown for CRS matrix.
1144  I - row index of the element to modify, 0<=I<M
1145  J - column index of the element to modify, 0<=J<N
1146  V - value to add, must be finite number
1147 
1148 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1149  S - modified matrix
1150 
1151 NOTE 1: when S[i,j] is exactly zero after modification, it is deleted
1152 from the table.
1153 
1154  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1155  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1156 *************************************************************************/
1157 void sparseadd(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, const ae_int_t j, const double v, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1158 
1159 
1160 /*************************************************************************
1161 This function modifies S[i,j] - element of the sparse matrix.
1162 
1163 For Hash-based storage format:
1164 * this function can be called at any moment - during matrix initialization
1165  or later
1166 * new value can be zero or non-zero. In case new value of S[i,j] is zero,
1167  this element is deleted from the table.
1168 * this function has no effect when called with zero V for non-existent
1169  element.
1170 
1171 For CRS-bases storage format:
1172 * this function can be called ONLY DURING MATRIX INITIALIZATION
1173 * zero values are stored in the matrix similarly to non-zero ones
1174 * elements must be initialized in correct order - from top row to bottom,
1175  within row - from left to right.
1176 
1177 For SKS storage:
1178 * this function can be called at any moment - during matrix initialization
1179  or later
1180 * zero values are stored in the matrix similarly to non-zero ones
1181 * this function CAN NOT be called for non-existent (outside of the band
1182  specified during SKS matrix creation) elements. Say, if you created SKS
1183  matrix with bandwidth=2 and tried to call sparseset(s,0,10,VAL), an
1184  exception will be generated.
1185 
1186 INPUT PARAMETERS
1187  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table, SKS or CRS format.
1188  I - row index of the element to modify, 0<=I<M
1189  J - column index of the element to modify, 0<=J<N
1190  V - value to set, must be finite number, can be zero
1191 
1192 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1193  S - modified matrix
1194 
1195  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1196  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1197 *************************************************************************/
1198 void sparseset(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, const ae_int_t j, const double v, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1199 
1200 
1201 /*************************************************************************
1202 This function returns S[i,j] - element of the sparse matrix. Matrix can
1203 be in any mode (Hash-Table, CRS, SKS), but this function is less efficient
1204 for CRS matrices. Hash-Table and SKS matrices can find element in O(1)
1205 time, while CRS matrices need O(log(RS)) time, where RS is an number of
1206 non-zero elements in a row.
1207 
1208 INPUT PARAMETERS
1209  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table representation.
1210  Exception will be thrown for CRS matrix.
1211  I - row index of the element to modify, 0<=I<M
1212  J - column index of the element to modify, 0<=J<N
1213 
1214 RESULT
1215  value of S[I,J] or zero (in case no element with such index is found)
1216 
1217  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1218  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1219 *************************************************************************/
1220 double sparseget(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, const ae_int_t j, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1221

1223 /*************************************************************************
1224 This function returns I-th diagonal element of the sparse matrix.
1225 
1226 Matrix can be in any mode (Hash-Table or CRS storage), but this function
1227 is most efficient for CRS matrices - it requires less than 50 CPU cycles
1228 to extract diagonal element. For Hash-Table matrices we still have O(1)
1229 query time, but function is many times slower.
1230 
1231 INPUT PARAMETERS
1232  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table representation.
1233  Exception will be thrown for CRS matrix.
1234  I - index of the element to modify, 0<=I<min(M,N)
1235 
1236 RESULT
1237  value of S[I,I] or zero (in case no element with such index is found)
1238 
1239  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1240  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1241 *************************************************************************/
1242 double sparsegetdiagonal(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1513 /*************************************************************************
1514 This function calculates matrix-vector product op(S)*x, when x is vector,
1515 S is symmetric triangular matrix, op(S) is transposition or no operation.
1516 Matrix S must be stored in CRS or SKS format (exception will be thrown
1517 otherwise).
1518 
1519 INPUT PARAMETERS
1520  S - sparse square matrix in CRS or SKS format.
1521  IsUpper - whether upper or lower triangle of S is used:
1522  * if upper triangle is given, only S[i,j] for j>=i
1523  are used, and lower triangle is ignored (it can be
1524  empty - these elements are not referenced at all).
1525  * if lower triangle is given, only S[i,j] for j<=i
1526  are used, and upper triangle is ignored.
1527  IsUnit - unit or non-unit diagonal:
1528  * if True, diagonal elements of triangular matrix are
1529  considered equal to 1.0. Actual elements stored in
1530  S are not referenced at all.
1531  * if False, diagonal stored in S is used
1532  OpType - operation type:
1533  * if 0, S*x is calculated
1534  * if 1, (S^T)*x is calculated (transposition)
1535  X - array[N] which stores input vector. For performance
1536  reasons we make only quick checks - we check that
1537  array size is at least N, but we do not check for
1538  NAN's or INF's.
1539  Y - possibly preallocated input buffer. Automatically
1540  resized if its size is too small.
1541 
1542 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1543  Y - array[N], op(S)*x
1544 
1545 NOTE: this function throws exception when called for non-CRS/SKS matrix.
1546 You must convert your matrix with SparseConvertToCRS/SKS() before using
1547 this function.
1548 
1549  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1550  Copyright 20.01.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1551 *************************************************************************/
1552 void sparsetrmv(const sparsematrix &s, const bool isupper, const bool isunit, const ae_int_t optype, const real_1d_array &x, real_1d_array &y, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1554 
1555 /*************************************************************************
1556 This function solves linear system op(S)*y=x where x is vector, S is
1557 symmetric triangular matrix, op(S) is transposition or no operation.
1558 Matrix S must be stored in CRS or SKS format (exception will be thrown
1559 otherwise).
1560 
1561 INPUT PARAMETERS
1562  S - sparse square matrix in CRS or SKS format.
1563  IsUpper - whether upper or lower triangle of S is used:
1564  * if upper triangle is given, only S[i,j] for j>=i
1565  are used, and lower triangle is ignored (it can be
1566  empty - these elements are not referenced at all).
1567  * if lower triangle is given, only S[i,j] for j<=i
1568  are used, and upper triangle is ignored.
1569  IsUnit - unit or non-unit diagonal:
1570  * if True, diagonal elements of triangular matrix are
1571  considered equal to 1.0. Actual elements stored in
1572  S are not referenced at all.
1573  * if False, diagonal stored in S is used. It is your
1574  responsibility to make sure that diagonal is
1575  non-zero.
1576  OpType - operation type:
1577  * if 0, S*x is calculated
1578  * if 1, (S^T)*x is calculated (transposition)
1579  X - array[N] which stores input vector. For performance
1580  reasons we make only quick checks - we check that
1581  array size is at least N, but we do not check for
1582  NAN's or INF's.
1583 
1584 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1585  X - array[N], inv(op(S))*x
1586 
1587 NOTE: this function throws exception when called for non-CRS/SKS matrix.
1588  You must convert your matrix with SparseConvertToCRS/SKS() before
1589  using this function.
1590 
1591 NOTE: no assertion or tests are done during algorithm operation. It is
1592  your responsibility to provide invertible matrix to algorithm.
1593 
1594  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1595  Copyright 20.01.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1596 *************************************************************************/
1597 void sparsetrsv(const sparsematrix &s, const bool isupper, const bool isunit, const ae_int_t optype, const real_1d_array &x, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

1600 /*************************************************************************
1601 This procedure resizes Hash-Table matrix. It can be called when you have
1602 deleted too many elements from the matrix, and you want to free unneeded
1603 memory.
1604 
1605  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1606  Copyright 14.10.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
1607 *************************************************************************/
1608 void sparseresizematrix(const sparsematrix &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1609 
1610 
1611 /*************************************************************************
1612 This function is used to enumerate all elements of the sparse matrix.
1613 Before first call user initializes T0 and T1 counters by zero. These
1614 counters are used to remember current position in a matrix; after each
1615 call they are updated by the function.
1616 
1617 Subsequent calls to this function return non-zero elements of the sparse
1618 matrix, one by one. If you enumerate CRS matrix, matrix is traversed from
1619 left to right, from top to bottom. In case you enumerate matrix stored as
1620 Hash table, elements are returned in random order.
1621 
1622 EXAMPLE
1623  > T0=0
1624  > T1=0
1625  > while SparseEnumerate(S,T0,T1,I,J,V) do
1626  > ....do something with I,J,V
1627 
1628 INPUT PARAMETERS
1629  S - sparse M*N matrix in Hash-Table or CRS representation.
1630  T0 - internal counter
1631  T1 - internal counter
1632 
1633 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1634  T0 - new value of the internal counter
1635  T1 - new value of the internal counter
1636  I - row index of non-zero element, 0<=I<M.
1637  J - column index of non-zero element, 0<=J<N
1638  V - value of the T-th element
1639 
1640 RESULT
1641  True in case of success (next non-zero element was retrieved)
1642  False in case all non-zero elements were enumerated
1643 
1644 NOTE: you may call SparseRewriteExisting() during enumeration, but it is
1645  THE ONLY matrix modification function you can call!!! Other
1646  matrix modification functions should not be called during enumeration!
1647 
1648  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1649  Copyright 14.03.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
1650 *************************************************************************/
1651 bool sparseenumerate(const sparsematrix &s, ae_int_t &t0, ae_int_t &t1, ae_int_t &i, ae_int_t &j, double &v, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1652 
1653 
1654 /*************************************************************************
1655 This function rewrites existing (non-zero) element. It returns True if
1656 element exists or False, when it is called for non-existing (zero)
1657 element.
1658 
1659 This function works with any kind of the matrix.
1660 
1661 The purpose of this function is to provide convenient thread-safe way to
1662 modify sparse matrix. Such modification (already existing element is
1663 rewritten) is guaranteed to be thread-safe without any synchronization, as
1664 long as different threads modify different elements.
1665 
1666 INPUT PARAMETERS
1667  S - sparse M*N matrix in any kind of representation
1668  (Hash, SKS, CRS).
1669  I - row index of non-zero element to modify, 0<=I<M
1670  J - column index of non-zero element to modify, 0<=J<N
1671  V - value to rewrite, must be finite number
1672 
1673 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
1674  S - modified matrix
1675 RESULT
1676  True in case when element exists
1677  False in case when element doesn't exist or it is zero
1678 
1679  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1680  Copyright 14.03.2012 by Bochkanov Sergey
1681 *************************************************************************/
1682 bool sparserewriteexisting(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, const ae_int_t j, const double v, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1683 
1684 
1685 /*************************************************************************
1686 This function returns I-th row of the sparse matrix. Matrix must be stored
1687 in CRS or SKS format.
1688 
1689 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1690  S - sparse M*N matrix in CRS format
1691  I - row index, 0<=I<M
1692  IRow - output buffer, can be preallocated. In case buffer
1693  size is too small to store I-th row, it is
1694  automatically reallocated.
1695 
1696 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1697  IRow - array[M], I-th row.
1698 
1699 NOTE: this function has O(N) running time, where N is a column count. It
1700  allocates and fills N-element array, even although most of its
1701  elemets are zero.
1702 
1703 NOTE: If you have O(non-zeros-per-row) time and memory requirements, use
1704  SparseGetCompressedRow() function. It returns data in compressed
1705  format.
1706 
1707 NOTE: when incorrect I (outside of [0,M-1]) or matrix (non CRS/SKS)
1708  is passed, this function throws exception.
1709 
1710  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1711  Copyright 10.12.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1712 *************************************************************************/
1713 void sparsegetrow(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, real_1d_array &irow, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1714 
1715 
1716 /*************************************************************************
1717 This function returns I-th row of the sparse matrix IN COMPRESSED FORMAT -
1718 only non-zero elements are returned (with their indexes). Matrix must be
1719 stored in CRS or SKS format.
1720 
1721 INPUT PARAMETERS:
1722  S - sparse M*N matrix in CRS format
1723  I - row index, 0<=I<M
1724  ColIdx - output buffer for column indexes, can be preallocated.
1725  In case buffer size is too small to store I-th row, it
1726  is automatically reallocated.
1727  Vals - output buffer for values, can be preallocated. In case
1728  buffer size is too small to store I-th row, it is
1729  automatically reallocated.
1730 
1731 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
1732  ColIdx - column indexes of non-zero elements, sorted by
1733  ascending. Symbolically non-zero elements are counted
1734  (i.e. if you allocated place for element, but it has
1735  zero numerical value - it is counted).
1736  Vals - values. Vals[K] stores value of matrix element with
1737  indexes (I,ColIdx[K]). Symbolically non-zero elements
1738  are counted (i.e. if you allocated place for element,
1739  but it has zero numerical value - it is counted).
1740  NZCnt - number of symbolically non-zero elements per row.
1741 
1742 NOTE: when incorrect I (outside of [0,M-1]) or matrix (non CRS/SKS)
1743  is passed, this function throws exception.
1744 
1745 NOTE: this function may allocate additional, unnecessary place for ColIdx
1746  and Vals arrays. It is dictated by performance reasons - on SKS
1747  matrices it is faster to allocate space at the beginning with
1748  some "extra"-space, than performing two passes over matrix - first
1749  time to calculate exact space required for data, second time - to
1750  store data itself.
1751 
1752  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
1753  Copyright 10.12.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey
1754 *************************************************************************/
1755 void sparsegetcompressedrow(const sparsematrix &s, const ae_int_t i, integer_1d_array &colidx, real_1d_array &vals, ae_int_t &nzcnt, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
1756

1794 /*************************************************************************

1796 format.

1800  Fmt - desired storage format of the output, as returned by
1801  SparseGetMatrixType() function:

1804  * 2 for SKS
1805

1811  recommend to use out-of-place buffered conversion functions, like

2153 /*************************************************************************
2154 The function returns number of strictly upper triangular non-zero elements
2155 in the matrix. It counts SYMBOLICALLY non-zero elements, i.e. entries
2156 in the sparse matrix data structure. If some element has zero numerical
2157 value, it is still counted.
2158 
2159 This function has different cost for different types of matrices:
2160 * for hash-based matrices it involves complete pass over entire hash-table
2161  with O(NNZ) cost, where NNZ is number of non-zero elements
2162 * for CRS and SKS matrix types cost of counting is O(N) (N - matrix size).
2163 
2164 RESULT: number of non-zero elements strictly above main diagonal
2165 
2166  -- ALGLIB PROJECT --
2167  Copyright 12.02.2014 by Bochkanov Sergey

2177 
2178 This function has different cost for different types of matrices:
2179 * for hash-based matrices it involves complete pass over entire hash-table

2181 * for CRS and SKS matrix types cost of counting is O(N) (N - matrix size).

2422 /*************************************************************************
2423 This subroutine solves linear system op(A)*x=b where:
2424 * A is NxN upper/lower triangular/unitriangular matrix
2425 * X and B are Nx1 vectors
2426 * "op" may be identity transformation, transposition, conjugate transposition
2427 
2428 Solution replaces X.
2429 
2430 IMPORTANT: * no overflow/underflow/denegeracy tests is performed.
2431  * no integrity checks for operand sizes, out-of-bounds accesses
2432  and so on is performed
2433 
2434 INPUT PARAMETERS
2435  N - matrix size, N>=0
2436  A - matrix, actial matrix is stored in A[IA:IA+N-1,JA:JA+N-1]
2437  IA - submatrix offset
2438  JA - submatrix offset
2439  IsUpper - whether matrix is upper triangular
2440  IsUnit - whether matrix is unitriangular
2441  OpType - transformation type:
2442  * 0 - no transformation
2443  * 1 - transposition
2444  X - right part, actual vector is stored in X[IX:IX+N-1]
2445  IX - offset
2446 
2447 OUTPUT PARAMETERS
2448  X - solution replaces elements X[IX:IX+N-1]
2449 
2450  -- ALGLIB routine / remastering of LAPACK's DTRSV --
2451  (c) 2017 Bochkanov Sergey - converted to ALGLIB
2452  (c) 2016 Reference BLAS level1 routine (LAPACK version 3.7.0)
2453  Reference BLAS is a software package provided by Univ. of Tennessee,
2454  Univ. of California Berkeley, Univ. of Colorado Denver and NAG Ltd.
2455 *************************************************************************/

2629 /*************************************************************************
2630 This subroutine calculates C=alpha*A*A^H+beta*C or C=alpha*A^H*A+beta*C
2631 where:
2632 * C is NxN Hermitian matrix given by its upper/lower triangle
2633 * A is NxK matrix when A*A^H is calculated, KxN matrix otherwise
2634 
2635 Additional info:
2636 * multiplication result replaces C. If Beta=0, C elements are not used in
2637  calculations (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2638 * if Alpha=0, A is not used (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2639 * if both Beta and Alpha are zero, C is filled by zeros.

2642  !
2643  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
2644  ! of this function:

2648  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
2649  !

2651  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
2652  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.

2654 INPUT PARAMETERS
2655  N - matrix size, N>=0
2656  K - matrix size, K>=0
2657  Alpha - coefficient
2658  A - matrix
2659  IA - submatrix offset (row index)
2660  JA - submatrix offset (column index)
2661  OpTypeA - multiplication type:
2662  * 0 - A*A^H is calculated
2663  * 2 - A^H*A is calculated
2664  Beta - coefficient
2665  C - preallocated input/output matrix
2666  IC - submatrix offset (row index)

2668  IsUpper - whether upper or lower triangle of C is updated;
2669  this function updates only one half of C, leaving
2670  other half unchanged (not referenced at all).

2733 
2734 Additional info:
2735 * cache-oblivious algorithm is used.
2736 * multiplication result replaces C. If Beta=0, C elements are not used in
2737  calculations (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2738 * if Alpha=0, A is not used (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2739 * if both Beta and Alpha are zero, C is filled by zeros.
2740 
2741  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
2742  !
2743  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
2744  ! of this function:
2745  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
2746  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
2747  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
2748  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
2749  !
2750  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
2751  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
2752  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
2753 
2754 IMPORTANT:
2755 
2756 This function does NOT preallocate output matrix C, it MUST be preallocated
2757 by caller prior to calling this function. In case C does not have enough
2758 space to store result, exception will be generated.
2759 
2760 INPUT PARAMETERS
2761  M - matrix size, M>0
2762  N - matrix size, N>0
2763  K - matrix size, K>0
2764  Alpha - coefficient
2765  A - matrix
2766  IA - submatrix offset
2767  JA - submatrix offset
2768  OpTypeA - transformation type:
2769  * 0 - no transformation
2770  * 1 - transposition
2771  * 2 - conjugate transposition
2772  B - matrix
2773  IB - submatrix offset
2774  JB - submatrix offset
2775  OpTypeB - transformation type:
2776  * 0 - no transformation
2777  * 1 - transposition
2778  * 2 - conjugate transposition
2779  Beta - coefficient
2780  C - matrix (PREALLOCATED, large enough to store result)
2781  IC - submatrix offset
2782  JC - submatrix offset
2783 
2784  -- ALGLIB routine --
2785  2009-2019
2786  Bochkanov Sergey
2787 *************************************************************************/
2788 void cmatrixgemm(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t k, const alglib::complex alpha, const complex_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t ia, const ae_int_t ja, const ae_int_t optypea, const complex_2d_array &b, const ae_int_t ib, const ae_int_t jb, const ae_int_t optypeb, const alglib::complex beta, const complex_2d_array &c, const ae_int_t ic, const ae_int_t jc, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

2797

2799 * cache-oblivious algorithm is used.
2800 * multiplication result replaces C. If Beta=0, C elements are not used in
2801  calculations (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2802 * if Alpha=0, A is not used (not multiplied by zero - just not referenced)
2803 * if both Beta and Alpha are zero, C is filled by zeros.

2812  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)

2815  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
2816  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
2817

2831  JA - submatrix offset

2871 
2872 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:

2876  "The Efficient Generation of Random Orthogonal Matrices with an
2877  Application to Condition Estimators".

2880  * takes an NxN one

2883  it to the smaller matrix (embedded in the larger size with a 1 at
2884  the bottom right corner).

3218 /*************************************************************************
3219 Cache-oblivious Cholesky decomposition
3220 
3221 The algorithm computes Cholesky decomposition of a Hermitian positive-
3222 definite matrix. The result of an algorithm is a representation of A as
3223 A=U'*U or A=L*L' (here X' denotes conj(X^T)).
3224 
3225  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
3226  !
3227  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
3228  ! of this function:
3229  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
3230  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
3231  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
3232  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
3233  !
3234  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
3235  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
3236  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
3237 
3238 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3239  A - upper or lower triangle of a factorized matrix.
3240  array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3241  N - size of matrix A.
3242  IsUpper - if IsUpper=True, then A contains an upper triangle of
3243  a symmetric matrix, otherwise A contains a lower one.
3244 
3245 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3246  A - the result of factorization. If IsUpper=True, then
3247  the upper triangle contains matrix U, so that A = U'*U,
3248  and the elements below the main diagonal are not modified.
3249  Similarly, if IsUpper = False.
3250 
3251 RESULT:
3252  If the matrix is positive-definite, the function returns True.
3253  Otherwise, the function returns False. Contents of A is not determined
3254  in such case.
3255 
3256  -- ALGLIB routine --
3257  15.12.2009-22.01.2018
3258  Bochkanov Sergey
3259 *************************************************************************/
3260 bool hpdmatrixcholesky(complex_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3308 /*************************************************************************
3309 Update of Cholesky decomposition: rank-1 update to original A. "Buffered"
3310 version which uses preallocated buffer which is saved between subsequent
3311 function calls.
3312 
3313 This function uses internally allocated buffer which is not saved between
3314 subsequent calls. So, if you perform a lot of subsequent updates,
3315 we recommend you to use "buffered" version of this function:
3316 SPDMatrixCholeskyUpdateAdd1Buf().
3317 
3318 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3319  A - upper or lower Cholesky factor.
3320  array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3321  Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3322  N - size of matrix A, N>0
3323  IsUpper - if IsUpper=True, then A contains upper Cholesky factor;
3324  otherwise A contains a lower one.
3325  U - array[N], rank-1 update to A: A_mod = A + u*u'
3326  Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3327  BufR - possibly preallocated buffer; automatically resized if
3328  needed. It is recommended to reuse this buffer if you
3329  perform a lot of subsequent decompositions.
3330 
3331 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3332  A - updated factorization. If IsUpper=True, then the upper
3333  triangle contains matrix U, and the elements below the main
3334  diagonal are not modified. Similarly, if IsUpper = False.
3335 
3336 NOTE: this function always succeeds, so it does not return completion code
3337 
3338 NOTE: this function checks sizes of input arrays, but it does NOT checks
3339  for presence of infinities or NAN's.
3340 
3341  -- ALGLIB --
3342  03.02.2014
3343  Sergey Bochkanov
3344 *************************************************************************/
3345 void spdmatrixcholeskyupdateadd1(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const real_1d_array &u, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3347 
3348 /*************************************************************************
3349 Update of Cholesky decomposition: "fixing" some variables.
3350 
3351 This function uses internally allocated buffer which is not saved between
3352 subsequent calls. So, if you perform a lot of subsequent updates,
3353 we recommend you to use "buffered" version of this function:
3354 SPDMatrixCholeskyUpdateFixBuf().
3355 
3356 "FIXING" EXPLAINED:
3357 
3358  Suppose we have N*N positive definite matrix A. "Fixing" some variable
3359  means filling corresponding row/column of A by zeros, and setting
3360  diagonal element to 1.
3361 
3362  For example, if we fix 2nd variable in 4*4 matrix A, it becomes Af:
3363 
3364  ( A00 A01 A02 A03 ) ( Af00 0 Af02 Af03 )
3365  ( A10 A11 A12 A13 ) ( 0 1 0 0 )
3366  ( A20 A21 A22 A23 ) => ( Af20 0 Af22 Af23 )
3367  ( A30 A31 A32 A33 ) ( Af30 0 Af32 Af33 )
3368 
3369  If we have Cholesky decomposition of A, it must be recalculated after
3370  variables were fixed. However, it is possible to use efficient
3371  algorithm, which needs O(K*N^2) time to "fix" K variables, given
3372  Cholesky decomposition of original, "unfixed" A.
3373 
3374 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3375  A - upper or lower Cholesky factor.
3376  array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3377  Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3378  N - size of matrix A, N>0
3379  IsUpper - if IsUpper=True, then A contains upper Cholesky factor;
3380  otherwise A contains a lower one.
3381  Fix - array[N], I-th element is True if I-th variable must be
3382  fixed. Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3383  BufR - possibly preallocated buffer; automatically resized if
3384  needed. It is recommended to reuse this buffer if you
3385  perform a lot of subsequent decompositions.
3386 
3387 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3388  A - updated factorization. If IsUpper=True, then the upper
3389  triangle contains matrix U, and the elements below the main
3390  diagonal are not modified. Similarly, if IsUpper = False.
3391 
3392 NOTE: this function always succeeds, so it does not return completion code
3393 
3394 NOTE: this function checks sizes of input arrays, but it does NOT checks
3395  for presence of infinities or NAN's.
3396 
3397 NOTE: this function is efficient only for moderate amount of updated
3398  variables - say, 0.1*N or 0.3*N. For larger amount of variables it
3399  will still work, but you may get better performance with
3400  straightforward Cholesky.
3401 
3402  -- ALGLIB --
3403  03.02.2014
3404  Sergey Bochkanov
3405 *************************************************************************/
3406 void spdmatrixcholeskyupdatefix(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const boolean_1d_array &fix, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3407 
3408 
3409 /*************************************************************************
3410 Update of Cholesky decomposition: rank-1 update to original A. "Buffered"
3411 version which uses preallocated buffer which is saved between subsequent
3412 function calls.
3413 
3414 See comments for SPDMatrixCholeskyUpdateAdd1() for more information.
3415 
3416 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3417  A - upper or lower Cholesky factor.
3418  array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3419  Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3420  N - size of matrix A, N>0
3421  IsUpper - if IsUpper=True, then A contains upper Cholesky factor;
3422  otherwise A contains a lower one.
3423  U - array[N], rank-1 update to A: A_mod = A + u*u'
3424  Exception is thrown if array size is too small.
3425  BufR - possibly preallocated buffer; automatically resized if
3426  needed. It is recommended to reuse this buffer if you
3427  perform a lot of subsequent decompositions.
3428 
3429 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3430  A - updated factorization. If IsUpper=True, then the upper
3431  triangle contains matrix U, and the elements below the main
3432  diagonal are not modified. Similarly, if IsUpper = False.

3434  -- ALGLIB --
3435  03.02.2014
3436  Sergey Bochkanov
3437 *************************************************************************/
3438 void spdmatrixcholeskyupdateadd1buf(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const real_1d_array &u, real_1d_array &bufr, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

3445 
3446 See comments for SPDMatrixCholeskyUpdateFix() for more information.
3447 
3448 INPUT PARAMETERS:

3473 /*************************************************************************
3474 Sparse Cholesky decomposition for skyline matrixm using in-place algorithm
3475 without allocating additional storage.
3476 
3477 The algorithm computes Cholesky decomposition of a symmetric positive-
3478 definite sparse matrix. The result of an algorithm is a representation of
3479 A as A=U^T*U or A=L*L^T
3480 
3481 This function is a more efficient alternative to general, but slower
3482 SparseCholeskyX(), because it does not create temporary copies of the
3483 target. It performs factorization in-place, which gives best performance
3484 on low-profile matrices. Its drawback, however, is that it can not perform
3485 profile-reducing permutation of input matrix.
3486 
3487 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3488  A - sparse matrix in skyline storage (SKS) format.
3489  N - size of matrix A (can be smaller than actual size of A)
3490  IsUpper - if IsUpper=True, then factorization is performed on upper
3491  triangle. Another triangle is ignored (it may contant some
3492  data, but it is not changed).
3493 
3494 
3495 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
3496  A - the result of factorization, stored in SKS. If IsUpper=True,
3497  then the upper triangle contains matrix U, such that
3498  A = U^T*U. Lower triangle is not changed.
3499  Similarly, if IsUpper = False. In this case L is returned,
3500  and we have A = L*(L^T).
3501  Note that THIS function does not perform permutation of
3502  rows to reduce bandwidth.
3503 
3504 RESULT:
3505  If the matrix is positive-definite, the function returns True.
3506  Otherwise, the function returns False. Contents of A is not determined
3507  in such case.
3508 
3509 NOTE: for performance reasons this function does NOT check that input
3510  matrix includes only finite values. It is your responsibility to
3511  make sure that there are no infinite or NAN values in the matrix.
3512 
3513  -- ALGLIB routine --
3514  16.01.2014
3515  Bochkanov Sergey
3516 *************************************************************************/
3517 bool sparsecholeskyskyline(const sparsematrix &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
3518 #endif

3521 /*************************************************************************
3522 Estimate of a matrix condition number (1-norm)

3524 The algorithm calculates a lower bound of the condition number. In this case,
3525 the algorithm does not return a lower bound of the condition number, but an
3526 inverse number (to avoid an overflow in case of a singular matrix).
3527 
3528 Input parameters:
3529  A - matrix. Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3530  N - size of matrix A.
3531 
3532 Result: 1/LowerBound(cond(A))
3533 
3534 NOTE:
3535  if k(A) is very large, then matrix is assumed degenerate, k(A)=INF,
3536  0.0 is returned in such cases.

3565 the algorithm does not return a lower bound of the condition number, but an
3566 inverse number (to avoid an overflow in case of a singular matrix).
3567 
3568 It should be noted that 1-norm and inf-norm of condition numbers of symmetric
3569 matrices are equal, so the algorithm doesn't take into account the
3570 differences between these types of norms.

3576  N - size of matrix A.
3577  IsUpper - storage format.
3578 
3579 Result:
3580  1/LowerBound(cond(A)), if matrix A is positive definite,
3581  -1, if matrix A is not positive definite, and its condition number
3582  could not be found by this algorithm.
3583 
3584 NOTE:
3585  if k(A) is very large, then matrix is assumed degenerate, k(A)=INF,
3586  0.0 is returned in such cases.
3587 *************************************************************************/

3887 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_MATINV) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
3888 /*************************************************************************
3889 Inversion of a matrix given by its LU decomposition.
3890 
3891  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
3892  !
3893  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
3894  ! of this function:
3895  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
3896  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
3897  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
3898  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
3899  !
3900  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
3901  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
3902  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
3903 
3904 INPUT PARAMETERS:
3905  A - LU decomposition of the matrix
3906  (output of RMatrixLU subroutine).
3907  Pivots - table of permutations
3908  (the output of RMatrixLU subroutine).
3909  N - size of matrix A (optional) :
3910  * if given, only principal NxN submatrix is processed and
3911  overwritten. other elements are unchanged.
3912  * if not given, size is automatically determined from
3913  matrix size (A must be square matrix)
3914

3917  * -3 A is singular, or VERY close to singular.
3918  it is filled by zeros in such cases.
3919  * 1 task is solved (but matrix A may be ill-conditioned,
3920  check R1/RInf parameters for condition numbers).
3921  Rep - solver report, see below for more info
3922  A - inverse of matrix A.
3923  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
3924

3926 
3927 Subroutine sets following fields of the Rep structure:
3928 * R1 reciprocal of condition number: 1/cond(A), 1-norm.

4253 /*************************************************************************
4254 Triangular matrix inverse (real)
4255 
4256 The subroutine inverts the following types of matrices:
4257  * upper triangular
4258  * upper triangular with unit diagonal
4259  * lower triangular
4260  * lower triangular with unit diagonal
4261 
4262 In case of an upper (lower) triangular matrix, the inverse matrix will
4263 also be upper (lower) triangular, and after the end of the algorithm, the
4264 inverse matrix replaces the source matrix. The elements below (above) the
4265 main diagonal are not changed by the algorithm.
4266 
4267 If the matrix has a unit diagonal, the inverse matrix also has a unit
4268 diagonal, and the diagonal elements are not passed to the algorithm.
4269 
4270  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4271  !
4272  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4273  ! of this function:
4274  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4275  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4276  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4277  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4278  !
4279  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4280  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4281  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4282 
4283 Input parameters:
4284  A - matrix, array[0..N-1, 0..N-1].
4285  N - size of matrix A (optional) :
4286  * if given, only principal NxN submatrix is processed and
4287  overwritten. other elements are unchanged.
4288  * if not given, size is automatically determined from
4289  matrix size (A must be square matrix)
4290  IsUpper - True, if the matrix is upper triangular.
4291  IsUnit - diagonal type (optional):
4292  * if True, matrix has unit diagonal (a[i,i] are NOT used)
4293  * if False, matrix diagonal is arbitrary
4294  * if not given, False is assumed
4295 
4296 Output parameters:
4297  Info - same as for RMatrixLUInverse
4298  Rep - same as for RMatrixLUInverse
4299  A - same as for RMatrixLUInverse.
4300 
4301  -- ALGLIB --
4302  Copyright 05.02.2010 by Bochkanov Sergey

4363 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_ORTFAC) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
4364 /*************************************************************************
4365 QR decomposition of a rectangular matrix of size MxN
4366 
4367  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4368  !
4369  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4370  ! of this function:
4371  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4372  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4373  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4374  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4375  !
4376  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4377  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4378  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4379 
4380 Input parameters:
4381  A - matrix A whose indexes range within [0..M-1, 0..N-1].
4382  M - number of rows in matrix A.
4383  N - number of columns in matrix A.
4384 
4385 Output parameters:
4386  A - matrices Q and R in compact form (see below).
4387  Tau - array of scalar factors which are used to form
4388  matrix Q. Array whose index ranges within [0.. Min(M-1,N-1)].
4389 
4390 Matrix A is represented as A = QR, where Q is an orthogonal matrix of size
4391 MxM, R - upper triangular (or upper trapezoid) matrix of size M x N.
4392 
4393 The elements of matrix R are located on and above the main diagonal of
4394 matrix A. The elements which are located in Tau array and below the main
4395 diagonal of matrix A are used to form matrix Q as follows:
4396 
4397 Matrix Q is represented as a product of elementary reflections
4398 
4399 Q = H(0)*H(2)*...*H(k-1),
4400 
4401 where k = min(m,n), and each H(i) is in the form
4402 
4403 H(i) = 1 - tau * v * (v^T)
4404 
4405 where tau is a scalar stored in Tau[I]; v - real vector,
4406 so that v(0:i-1) = 0, v(i) = 1, v(i+1:m-1) stored in A(i+1:m-1,i).
4407 
4408  -- ALGLIB routine --
4409  17.02.2010
4410  Bochkanov Sergey
4411 *************************************************************************/
4412 void rmatrixqr(real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, real_1d_array &tau, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4414 
4415 /*************************************************************************
4416 LQ decomposition of a rectangular matrix of size MxN
4417 
4418  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4419  !
4420  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4421  ! of this function:
4422  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4423  ! * multithreading support (C++ and C# versions)
4424  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4425  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4426  !
4427  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4428  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4429  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4430 
4431 Input parameters:
4432  A - matrix A whose indexes range within [0..M-1, 0..N-1].
4433  M - number of rows in matrix A.
4434  N - number of columns in matrix A.
4435 
4436 Output parameters:
4437  A - matrices L and Q in compact form (see below)
4438  Tau - array of scalar factors which are used to form
4439  matrix Q. Array whose index ranges within [0..Min(M,N)-1].
4440 
4441 Matrix A is represented as A = LQ, where Q is an orthogonal matrix of size
4442 MxM, L - lower triangular (or lower trapezoid) matrix of size M x N.
4443 
4444 The elements of matrix L are located on and below the main diagonal of
4445 matrix A. The elements which are located in Tau array and above the main
4446 diagonal of matrix A are used to form matrix Q as follows:
4447 
4448 Matrix Q is represented as a product of elementary reflections
4449 
4450 Q = H(k-1)*H(k-2)*...*H(1)*H(0),
4451 
4452 where k = min(m,n), and each H(i) is of the form
4453 
4454 H(i) = 1 - tau * v * (v^T)
4455 
4456 where tau is a scalar stored in Tau[I]; v - real vector, so that v(0:i-1)=0,
4457 v(i) = 1, v(i+1:n-1) stored in A(i,i+1:n-1).
4458

4764 /*************************************************************************
4765 Reduction of a rectangular matrix to bidiagonal form
4766 
4767 The algorithm reduces the rectangular matrix A to bidiagonal form by
4768 orthogonal transformations P and Q: A = Q*B*(P^T).
4769 
4770  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
4771  !
4772  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
4773  ! of this function:
4774  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
4775  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
4776  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
4777  !
4778  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
4779  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
4780  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
4781 
4782 Input parameters:
4783  A - source matrix. array[0..M-1, 0..N-1]
4784  M - number of rows in matrix A.
4785  N - number of columns in matrix A.
4786 
4787 Output parameters:
4788  A - matrices Q, B, P in compact form (see below).
4789  TauQ - scalar factors which are used to form matrix Q.
4790  TauP - scalar factors which are used to form matrix P.
4791 
4792 The main diagonal and one of the secondary diagonals of matrix A are
4793 replaced with bidiagonal matrix B. Other elements contain elementary
4794 reflections which form MxM matrix Q and NxN matrix P, respectively.
4795 
4796 If M>=N, B is the upper bidiagonal MxN matrix and is stored in the
4797 corresponding elements of matrix A. Matrix Q is represented as a
4798 product of elementary reflections Q = H(0)*H(1)*...*H(n-1), where
4799 H(i) = 1-tau*v*v'. Here tau is a scalar which is stored in TauQ[i], and
4800 vector v has the following structure: v(0:i-1)=0, v(i)=1, v(i+1:m-1) is
4801 stored in elements A(i+1:m-1,i). Matrix P is as follows: P =
4802 G(0)*G(1)*...*G(n-2), where G(i) = 1 - tau*u*u'. Tau is stored in TauP[i],
4803 u(0:i)=0, u(i+1)=1, u(i+2:n-1) is stored in elements A(i,i+2:n-1).
4804 
4805 If M<N, B is the lower bidiagonal MxN matrix and is stored in the
4806 corresponding elements of matrix A. Q = H(0)*H(1)*...*H(m-2), where
4807 H(i) = 1 - tau*v*v', tau is stored in TauQ, v(0:i)=0, v(i+1)=1, v(i+2:m-1)
4808 is stored in elements A(i+2:m-1,i). P = G(0)*G(1)*...*G(m-1),
4809 G(i) = 1-tau*u*u', tau is stored in TauP, u(0:i-1)=0, u(i)=1, u(i+1:n-1)
4810 is stored in A(i,i+1:n-1).
4811 
4812 EXAMPLE:
4813 
4814 m=6, n=5 (m > n): m=5, n=6 (m < n):
4815 
4816 ( d e u1 u1 u1 ) ( d u1 u1 u1 u1 u1 )
4817 ( v1 d e u2 u2 ) ( e d u2 u2 u2 u2 )
4818 ( v1 v2 d e u3 ) ( v1 e d u3 u3 u3 )
4819 ( v1 v2 v3 d e ) ( v1 v2 e d u4 u4 )
4820 ( v1 v2 v3 v4 d ) ( v1 v2 v3 e d u5 )
4821 ( v1 v2 v3 v4 v5 )
4822 
4823 Here vi and ui are vectors which form H(i) and G(i), and d and e -
4824 are the diagonal and off-diagonal elements of matrix B.
4825 
4826  -- LAPACK routine (version 3.0) --
4827  Univ. of Tennessee, Univ. of California Berkeley, NAG Ltd.,
4828  Courant Institute, Argonne National Lab, and Rice University
4829  September 30, 1994.
4830  Sergey Bochkanov, ALGLIB project, translation from FORTRAN to
4831  pseudocode, 2007-2010.
4832 *************************************************************************/
4833 void rmatrixbd(real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, real_1d_array &tauq, real_1d_array &taup, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

4976 /*************************************************************************

4987  otherwise IsUpper is False.
4988  D - the main diagonal.

4991  the value of IsUpper).
4992  Array index ranges within [0..Min(M,N)-1], the last
4993  element is not used.

5002 /*************************************************************************
5003 Reduction of a square matrix to upper Hessenberg form: Q'*A*Q = H,
5004 where Q is an orthogonal matrix, H - Hessenberg matrix.
5005 
5006  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5007  !
5008  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5009  ! of this function:
5010  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5011  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5012  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5013  !
5014  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5015  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5016  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5017 
5018 Input parameters:
5019  A - matrix A with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1]
5020  N - size of matrix A.
5021 
5022 Output parameters:
5023  A - matrices Q and P in compact form (see below).
5024  Tau - array of scalar factors which are used to form matrix Q.
5025  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-2]
5026 
5027 Matrix H is located on the main diagonal, on the lower secondary diagonal
5028 and above the main diagonal of matrix A. The elements which are used to
5029 form matrix Q are situated in array Tau and below the lower secondary
5030 diagonal of matrix A as follows:
5031 
5032 Matrix Q is represented as a product of elementary reflections
5033 
5034 Q = H(0)*H(2)*...*H(n-2),
5035 
5036 where each H(i) is given by
5037 
5038 H(i) = 1 - tau * v * (v^T)
5039 
5040 where tau is a scalar stored in Tau[I]; v - is a real vector,
5041 so that v(0:i) = 0, v(i+1) = 1, v(i+2:n-1) stored in A(i+2:n-1,i).
5042 
5043  -- LAPACK routine (version 3.0) --
5044  Univ. of Tennessee, Univ. of California Berkeley, NAG Ltd.,
5045  Courant Institute, Argonne National Lab, and Rice University
5046  October 31, 1992
5047 *************************************************************************/
5048 void rmatrixhessenberg(real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, real_1d_array &tau, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5100 /*************************************************************************
5101 Reduction of a symmetric matrix which is given by its higher or lower
5102 triangular part to a tridiagonal matrix using orthogonal similarity
5103 transformation: Q'*A*Q=T.
5104 
5105  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5106  !
5107  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5108  ! of this function:
5109  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5110  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5111  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5112  !
5113  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5114  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5115  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5116 
5117 Input parameters:
5118  A - matrix to be transformed
5119  array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
5120  N - size of matrix A.
5121  IsUpper - storage format. If IsUpper = True, then matrix A is given
5122  by its upper triangle, and the lower triangle is not used
5123  and not modified by the algorithm, and vice versa
5124  if IsUpper = False.
5125 
5126 Output parameters:
5127  A - matrices T and Q in compact form (see lower)
5128  Tau - array of factors which are forming matrices H(i)
5129  array with elements [0..N-2].
5130  D - main diagonal of symmetric matrix T.
5131  array with elements [0..N-1].
5132  E - secondary diagonal of symmetric matrix T.
5133  array with elements [0..N-2].
5134 
5135 
5136  If IsUpper=True, the matrix Q is represented as a product of elementary
5137  reflectors
5138 
5139  Q = H(n-2) . . . H(2) H(0).
5140 
5141  Each H(i) has the form
5142 
5143  H(i) = I - tau * v * v'
5144 
5145  where tau is a real scalar, and v is a real vector with
5146  v(i+1:n-1) = 0, v(i) = 1, v(0:i-1) is stored on exit in
5147  A(0:i-1,i+1), and tau in TAU(i).
5148 
5149  If IsUpper=False, the matrix Q is represented as a product of elementary
5150  reflectors
5151 
5152  Q = H(0) H(2) . . . H(n-2).
5153 
5154  Each H(i) has the form
5155 
5156  H(i) = I - tau * v * v'
5157 
5158  where tau is a real scalar, and v is a real vector with
5159  v(0:i) = 0, v(i+1) = 1, v(i+2:n-1) is stored on exit in A(i+2:n-1,i),
5160  and tau in TAU(i).
5161 
5162  The contents of A on exit are illustrated by the following examples
5163  with n = 5:
5164 
5165  if UPLO = 'U': if UPLO = 'L':
5166 
5167  ( d e v1 v2 v3 ) ( d )
5168  ( d e v2 v3 ) ( e d )
5169  ( d e v3 ) ( v0 e d )
5170  ( d e ) ( v0 v1 e d )
5171  ( d ) ( v0 v1 v2 e d )
5172 
5173  where d and e denote diagonal and off-diagonal elements of T, and vi
5174  denotes an element of the vector defining H(i).
5175 
5176  -- LAPACK routine (version 3.0) --
5177  Univ. of Tennessee, Univ. of California Berkeley, NAG Ltd.,
5178  Courant Institute, Argonne National Lab, and Rice University
5179  October 31, 1992
5180 *************************************************************************/

5336 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_BDSVD) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5337 /*************************************************************************
5338 Singular value decomposition of a bidiagonal matrix (extended algorithm)
5339 
5340 COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5341 
5342  ! Commercial version of ALGLIB includes one important improvement of
5343  ! this function, which can be used from C++ and C#:
5344  ! * Intel MKL support (lightweight Intel MKL is shipped with ALGLIB)
5345  !
5346  ! Intel MKL gives approximately constant (with respect to number of
5347  ! worker threads) acceleration factor which depends on CPU being used,
5348  ! problem size and "baseline" ALGLIB edition which is used for
5349  ! comparison.
5350  !
5351  ! Generally, commercial ALGLIB is several times faster than open-source
5352  ! generic C edition, and many times faster than open-source C# edition.
5353  !
5354  ! Multithreaded acceleration is NOT supported for this function.
5355  !
5356  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5357  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5358  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5359 
5360 The algorithm performs the singular value decomposition of a bidiagonal
5361 matrix B (upper or lower) representing it as B = Q*S*P^T, where Q and P -
5362 orthogonal matrices, S - diagonal matrix with non-negative elements on the
5363 main diagonal, in descending order.
5364 
5365 The algorithm finds singular values. In addition, the algorithm can
5366 calculate matrices Q and P (more precisely, not the matrices, but their
5367 product with given matrices U and VT - U*Q and (P^T)*VT)). Of course,
5368 matrices U and VT can be of any type, including identity. Furthermore, the
5369 algorithm can calculate Q'*C (this product is calculated more effectively
5370 than U*Q, because this calculation operates with rows instead of matrix
5371 columns).
5372 
5373 The feature of the algorithm is its ability to find all singular values
5374 including those which are arbitrarily close to 0 with relative accuracy
5375 close to machine precision. If the parameter IsFractionalAccuracyRequired
5376 is set to True, all singular values will have high relative accuracy close
5377 to machine precision. If the parameter is set to False, only the biggest
5378 singular value will have relative accuracy close to machine precision.
5379 The absolute error of other singular values is equal to the absolute error
5380 of the biggest singular value.
5381 
5382 Input parameters:
5383  D - main diagonal of matrix B.
5384  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
5385  E - superdiagonal (or subdiagonal) of matrix B.
5386  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-2].
5387  N - size of matrix B.
5388  IsUpper - True, if the matrix is upper bidiagonal.
5389  IsFractionalAccuracyRequired -
5390  THIS PARAMETER IS IGNORED SINCE ALGLIB 3.5.0
5391  SINGULAR VALUES ARE ALWAYS SEARCHED WITH HIGH ACCURACY.
5392  U - matrix to be multiplied by Q.
5393  Array whose indexes range within [0..NRU-1, 0..N-1].
5394  The matrix can be bigger, in that case only the submatrix
5395  [0..NRU-1, 0..N-1] will be multiplied by Q.
5396  NRU - number of rows in matrix U.
5397  C - matrix to be multiplied by Q'.
5398  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..NCC-1].
5399  The matrix can be bigger, in that case only the submatrix
5400  [0..N-1, 0..NCC-1] will be multiplied by Q'.
5401  NCC - number of columns in matrix C.
5402  VT - matrix to be multiplied by P^T.
5403  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..NCVT-1].
5404  The matrix can be bigger, in that case only the submatrix
5405  [0..N-1, 0..NCVT-1] will be multiplied by P^T.
5406  NCVT - number of columns in matrix VT.
5407 
5408 Output parameters:
5409  D - singular values of matrix B in descending order.
5410  U - if NRU>0, contains matrix U*Q.
5411  VT - if NCVT>0, contains matrix (P^T)*VT.
5412  C - if NCC>0, contains matrix Q'*C.
5413 
5414 Result:
5415  True, if the algorithm has converged.
5416  False, if the algorithm hasn't converged (rare case).
5417 
5418 NOTE: multiplication U*Q is performed by means of transposition to internal
5419  buffer, multiplication and backward transposition. It helps to avoid
5420  costly columnwise operations and speed-up algorithm.
5421 
5422 Additional information:
5423  The type of convergence is controlled by the internal parameter TOL.
5424  If the parameter is greater than 0, the singular values will have
5425  relative accuracy TOL. If TOL<0, the singular values will have
5426  absolute accuracy ABS(TOL)*norm(B).
5427  By default, |TOL| falls within the range of 10*Epsilon and 100*Epsilon,
5428  where Epsilon is the machine precision. It is not recommended to use
5429  TOL less than 10*Epsilon since this will considerably slow down the
5430  algorithm and may not lead to error decreasing.
5431 
5432 History:
5433  * 31 March, 2007.
5434  changed MAXITR from 6 to 12.
5435 
5436  -- LAPACK routine (version 3.0) --
5437  Univ. of Tennessee, Univ. of California Berkeley, NAG Ltd.,
5438  Courant Institute, Argonne National Lab, and Rice University
5439  October 31, 1999.
5440 *************************************************************************/
5441 bool rmatrixbdsvd(real_1d_array &d, const real_1d_array &e, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const bool isfractionalaccuracyrequired, real_2d_array &u, const ae_int_t nru, real_2d_array &c, const ae_int_t ncc, real_2d_array &vt, const ae_int_t ncvt, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5442 #endif
5443 
5444 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_SVD) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5445 /*************************************************************************
5446 Singular value decomposition of a rectangular matrix.
5447 
5448  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5449  !
5450  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5451  ! of this function:
5452  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5453  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5454  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5455  !
5456  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5457  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5458  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5459 
5460 The algorithm calculates the singular value decomposition of a matrix of
5461 size MxN: A = U * S * V^T
5462 
5463 The algorithm finds the singular values and, optionally, matrices U and V^T.
5464 The algorithm can find both first min(M,N) columns of matrix U and rows of
5465 matrix V^T (singular vectors), and matrices U and V^T wholly (of sizes MxM
5466 and NxN respectively).
5467 
5468 Take into account that the subroutine does not return matrix V but V^T.
5469 
5470 Input parameters:
5471  A - matrix to be decomposed.
5472  Array whose indexes range within [0..M-1, 0..N-1].
5473  M - number of rows in matrix A.
5474  N - number of columns in matrix A.
5475  UNeeded - 0, 1 or 2. See the description of the parameter U.
5476  VTNeeded - 0, 1 or 2. See the description of the parameter VT.
5477  AdditionalMemory -
5478  If the parameter:
5479  * equals 0, the algorithm doesn't use additional
5480  memory (lower requirements, lower performance).
5481  * equals 1, the algorithm uses additional
5482  memory of size min(M,N)*min(M,N) of real numbers.
5483  It often speeds up the algorithm.
5484  * equals 2, the algorithm uses additional
5485  memory of size M*min(M,N) of real numbers.
5486  It allows to get a maximum performance.
5487  The recommended value of the parameter is 2.
5488 
5489 Output parameters:
5490  W - contains singular values in descending order.
5491  U - if UNeeded=0, U isn't changed, the left singular vectors
5492  are not calculated.
5493  if Uneeded=1, U contains left singular vectors (first
5494  min(M,N) columns of matrix U). Array whose indexes range
5495  within [0..M-1, 0..Min(M,N)-1].
5496  if UNeeded=2, U contains matrix U wholly. Array whose
5497  indexes range within [0..M-1, 0..M-1].
5498  VT - if VTNeeded=0, VT isn't changed, the right singular vectors
5499  are not calculated.
5500  if VTNeeded=1, VT contains right singular vectors (first
5501  min(M,N) rows of matrix V^T). Array whose indexes range
5502  within [0..min(M,N)-1, 0..N-1].
5503  if VTNeeded=2, VT contains matrix V^T wholly. Array whose
5504  indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
5505 
5506  -- ALGLIB --
5507  Copyright 2005 by Bochkanov Sergey
5508 *************************************************************************/
5509 bool rmatrixsvd(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t uneeded, const ae_int_t vtneeded, const ae_int_t additionalmemory, real_1d_array &w, real_2d_array &u, real_2d_array &vt, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5510 #endif
5511 
5512 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_NORMESTIMATOR) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5513 /*************************************************************************
5514 This procedure initializes matrix norm estimator.
5515 
5516 USAGE:
5517 1. User initializes algorithm state with NormEstimatorCreate() call
5518 2. User calls NormEstimatorEstimateSparse() (or NormEstimatorIteration())
5519 3. User calls NormEstimatorResults() to get solution.
5520 
5521 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5522  M - number of rows in the matrix being estimated, M>0
5523  N - number of columns in the matrix being estimated, N>0
5524  NStart - number of random starting vectors
5525  recommended value - at least 5.
5526  NIts - number of iterations to do with best starting vector
5527  recommended value - at least 5.
5528 
5529 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5530  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5531 
5532 
5533 NOTE: this algorithm is effectively deterministic, i.e. it always returns
5534 same result when repeatedly called for the same matrix. In fact, algorithm
5535 uses randomized starting vectors, but internal random numbers generator
5536 always generates same sequence of the random values (it is a feature, not
5537 bug).
5538 
5539 Algorithm can be made non-deterministic with NormEstimatorSetSeed(0) call.
5540 
5541  -- ALGLIB --
5542  Copyright 06.12.2011 by Bochkanov Sergey
5543 *************************************************************************/
5544 void normestimatorcreate(const ae_int_t m, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t nstart, const ae_int_t nits, normestimatorstate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

5548 This function changes seed value used by algorithm. In some cases we need
5549 deterministic processing, i.e. subsequent calls must return equal results,
5550 in other cases we need non-deterministic algorithm which returns different
5551 results for the same matrix on every pass.
5552 
5553 Setting zero seed will lead to non-deterministic algorithm, while non-zero
5554 value will make our algorithm deterministic.
