5600 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_HSSCHUR) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5601 
5602 #endif
5603 
5604 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_EVD) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
5605 /*************************************************************************
5606 This function initializes subspace iteration solver. This solver is used
5607 to solve symmetric real eigenproblems where just a few (top K) eigenvalues
5608 and corresponding eigenvectors is required.
5609 
5610 This solver can be significantly faster than complete EVD decomposition
5611 in the following case:
5612 * when only just a small fraction of top eigenpairs of dense matrix is
5613  required. When K approaches N, this solver is slower than complete dense
5614  EVD
5615 * when problem matrix is sparse (and/or is not known explicitly, i.e. only
5616  matrix-matrix product can be performed)
5617 
5618 USAGE (explicit dense/sparse matrix):
5619 1. User initializes algorithm state with eigsubspacecreate() call
5620 2. [optional] User tunes solver parameters by calling eigsubspacesetcond()
5621  or other functions
5622 3. User calls eigsubspacesolvedense() or eigsubspacesolvesparse() methods,
5623  which take algorithm state and 2D array or alglib.sparsematrix object.
5624 
5625 USAGE (out-of-core mode):
5626 1. User initializes algorithm state with eigsubspacecreate() call
5627 2. [optional] User tunes solver parameters by calling eigsubspacesetcond()
5628  or other functions
5629 3. User activates out-of-core mode of the solver and repeatedly calls
5630  communication functions in a loop like below:
5631  > alglib.eigsubspaceoocstart(state)
5632  > while alglib.eigsubspaceooccontinue(state) do
5633  > alglib.eigsubspaceoocgetrequestinfo(state, out RequestType, out M)
5634  > alglib.eigsubspaceoocgetrequestdata(state, out X)
5635  > [calculate Y=A*X, with X=R^NxM]
5636  > alglib.eigsubspaceoocsendresult(state, in Y)
5637  > alglib.eigsubspaceoocstop(state, out W, out Z, out Report)
5638 
5639 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5640  N - problem dimensionality, N>0
5641  K - number of top eigenvector to calculate, 0<K<=N.
5642 
5643 OUTPUT PARAMETERS:
5644  State - structure which stores algorithm state
5645 
5646 NOTE: if you solve many similar EVD problems you may find it useful to
5647  reuse previous subspace as warm-start point for new EVD problem. It
5648  can be done with eigsubspacesetwarmstart() function.
5649 
5650  -- ALGLIB --
5651  Copyright 16.01.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
5652 *************************************************************************/
5653 void eigsubspacecreate(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t k, eigsubspacestate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5654 
5655 
5656 /*************************************************************************
5657 Buffered version of constructor which aims to reuse previously allocated
5658 memory as much as possible.
5659 
5660  -- ALGLIB --
5661  Copyright 16.01.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
5662 *************************************************************************/
5663 void eigsubspacecreatebuf(const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t k, const eigsubspacestate &state, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5664 
5665 
5666 /*************************************************************************
5667 This function sets stopping critera for the solver:
5668 * error in eigenvector/value allowed by solver
5669 * maximum number of iterations to perform
5670 
5671 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5672  State - solver structure
5673  Eps - eps>=0, with non-zero value used to tell solver that
5674  it can stop after all eigenvalues converged with
5675  error roughly proportional to eps*MAX(LAMBDA_MAX),
5676  where LAMBDA_MAX is a maximum eigenvalue.
5677  Zero value means that no check for precision is
5678  performed.
5679  MaxIts - maxits>=0, with non-zero value used to tell solver
5680  that it can stop after maxits steps (no matter how
5681  precise current estimate is)
5682 
5683 NOTE: passing eps=0 and maxits=0 results in automatic selection of
5684  moderate eps as stopping criteria (1.0E-6 in current implementation,
5685  but it may change without notice).
5686 
5687 NOTE: very small values of eps are possible (say, 1.0E-12), although the
5688  larger problem you solve (N and/or K), the harder it is to find
5689  precise eigenvectors because rounding errors tend to accumulate.
5690 
5691 NOTE: passing non-zero eps results in some performance penalty, roughly
5692  equal to 2N*(2K)^2 FLOPs per iteration. These additional computations
5693  are required in order to estimate current error in eigenvalues via
5694  Rayleigh-Ritz process.
5695  Most of this additional time is spent in construction of ~2Kx2K
5696  symmetric subproblem whose eigenvalues are checked with exact
5697  eigensolver.
5698  This additional time is negligible if you search for eigenvalues of
5699  the large dense matrix, but may become noticeable on highly sparse
5700  EVD problems, where cost of matrix-matrix product is low.
5701  If you set eps to exactly zero, Rayleigh-Ritz phase is completely
5702  turned off.
5703 
5704  -- ALGLIB --
5705  Copyright 16.01.2017 by Bochkanov Sergey
5706 *************************************************************************/
5707 void eigsubspacesetcond(const eigsubspacestate &state, const double eps, const ae_int_t maxits, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
5708

5715 INPUT PARAMETERS:
5716  State - solver structure
5717  UseWarmStart- either True or False

5977 /*************************************************************************
5978 Finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a symmetric matrix
5979 
5980 The algorithm finds eigen pairs of a symmetric matrix by reducing it to
5981 tridiagonal form and using the QL/QR algorithm.
5982 
5983  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
5984  !
5985  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
5986  ! of this function:
5987  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
5988  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
5989  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
5990  !
5991  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
5992  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
5993  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
5994 
5995 Input parameters:
5996  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
5997  triangular part.
5998  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
5999  N - size of matrix A.
6000  ZNeeded - flag controlling whether the eigenvectors are needed or not.
6001  If ZNeeded is equal to:
6002  * 0, the eigenvectors are not returned;
6003  * 1, the eigenvectors are returned.
6004  IsUpper - storage format.
6005 
6006 Output parameters:
6007  D - eigenvalues in ascending order.
6008  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6009  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6010  * 0, Z hasn't changed;
6011  * 1, Z contains the eigenvectors.
6012  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6013  The eigenvectors are stored in the matrix columns.
6014 
6015 Result:
6016  True, if the algorithm has converged.
6017  False, if the algorithm hasn't converged (rare case).
6018 
6019  -- ALGLIB --
6020  Copyright 2005-2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
6021 *************************************************************************/
6022 bool smatrixevd(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t zneeded, const bool isupper, real_1d_array &d, real_2d_array &z, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6025 /*************************************************************************
6026 Subroutine for finding the eigenvalues (and eigenvectors) of a symmetric
6027 matrix in a given half open interval (A, B] by using a bisection and
6028 inverse iteration
6029 
6030  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
6031  !
6032  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
6033  ! of this function:
6034  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
6035  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
6036  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
6037  !
6038  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
6039  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
6040  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
6041 
6042 Input parameters:
6043  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
6044  triangular part. Array [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6045  N - size of matrix A.
6046  ZNeeded - flag controlling whether the eigenvectors are needed or not.
6047  If ZNeeded is equal to:
6048  * 0, the eigenvectors are not returned;
6049  * 1, the eigenvectors are returned.
6050  IsUpperA - storage format of matrix A.
6051  B1, B2 - half open interval (B1, B2] to search eigenvalues in.
6052 
6053 Output parameters:
6054  M - number of eigenvalues found in a given half-interval (M>=0).
6055  W - array of the eigenvalues found.
6056  Array whose index ranges within [0..M-1].
6057  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6058  * 0, Z hasn't changed;
6059  * 1, Z contains eigenvectors.
6060  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..M-1].
6061  The eigenvectors are stored in the matrix columns.
6062 
6063 Result:
6064  True, if successful. M contains the number of eigenvalues in the given
6065  half-interval (could be equal to 0), W contains the eigenvalues,
6066  Z contains the eigenvectors (if needed).
6067 
6068  False, if the bisection method subroutine wasn't able to find the
6069  eigenvalues in the given interval or if the inverse iteration subroutine
6070  wasn't able to find all the corresponding eigenvectors.
6071  In that case, the eigenvalues and eigenvectors are not returned,
6072  M is equal to 0.
6073 
6074  -- ALGLIB --
6075  Copyright 07.01.2006 by Bochkanov Sergey
6076 *************************************************************************/
6077 bool smatrixevdr(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t zneeded, const bool isupper, const double b1, const double b2, ae_int_t &m, real_1d_array &w, real_2d_array &z, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6080 /*************************************************************************
6081 Subroutine for finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a symmetric
6082 matrix with given indexes by using bisection and inverse iteration methods.
6083 
6084 Input parameters:
6085  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
6086  triangular part. Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6087  N - size of matrix A.
6088  ZNeeded - flag controlling whether the eigenvectors are needed or not.
6089  If ZNeeded is equal to:
6090  * 0, the eigenvectors are not returned;
6091  * 1, the eigenvectors are returned.
6092  IsUpperA - storage format of matrix A.
6093  I1, I2 - index interval for searching (from I1 to I2).
6094  0 <= I1 <= I2 <= N-1.
6095 
6096 Output parameters:
6097  W - array of the eigenvalues found.
6098  Array whose index ranges within [0..I2-I1].
6099  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6100  * 0, Z hasn't changed;
6101  * 1, Z contains eigenvectors.
6102  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..I2-I1].
6103  In that case, the eigenvectors are stored in the matrix columns.
6104 
6105 Result:
6106  True, if successful. W contains the eigenvalues, Z contains the
6107  eigenvectors (if needed).
6108 
6109  False, if the bisection method subroutine wasn't able to find the
6110  eigenvalues in the given interval or if the inverse iteration subroutine
6111  wasn't able to find all the corresponding eigenvectors.
6112  In that case, the eigenvalues and eigenvectors are not returned.
6113 
6114  -- ALGLIB --
6115  Copyright 07.01.2006 by Bochkanov Sergey
6116 *************************************************************************/
6117 bool smatrixevdi(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t zneeded, const bool isupper, const ae_int_t i1, const ae_int_t i2, real_1d_array &w, real_2d_array &z, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6266 /*************************************************************************
6267 Finding the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a tridiagonal symmetric matrix
6268 
6269 The algorithm finds the eigen pairs of a tridiagonal symmetric matrix by
6270 using an QL/QR algorithm with implicit shifts.
6271 
6272  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
6273  !
6274  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
6275  ! of this function:
6276  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
6277  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
6278  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
6279  !
6280  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
6281  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
6282  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
6283 
6284 Input parameters:
6285  D - the main diagonal of a tridiagonal matrix.
6286  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6287  E - the secondary diagonal of a tridiagonal matrix.
6288  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-2].
6289  N - size of matrix A.
6290  ZNeeded - flag controlling whether the eigenvectors are needed or not.
6291  If ZNeeded is equal to:
6292  * 0, the eigenvectors are not needed;
6293  * 1, the eigenvectors of a tridiagonal matrix
6294  are multiplied by the square matrix Z. It is used if the
6295  tridiagonal matrix is obtained by the similarity
6296  transformation of a symmetric matrix;
6297  * 2, the eigenvectors of a tridiagonal matrix replace the
6298  square matrix Z;
6299  * 3, matrix Z contains the first row of the eigenvectors
6300  matrix.
6301  Z - if ZNeeded=1, Z contains the square matrix by which the
6302  eigenvectors are multiplied.
6303  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6304 
6305 Output parameters:
6306  D - eigenvalues in ascending order.
6307  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6308  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6309  * 0, Z hasn't changed;
6310  * 1, Z contains the product of a given matrix (from the left)
6311  and the eigenvectors matrix (from the right);
6312  * 2, Z contains the eigenvectors.
6313  * 3, Z contains the first row of the eigenvectors matrix.
6314  If ZNeeded<3, Z is the array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6315  In that case, the eigenvectors are stored in the matrix columns.
6316  If ZNeeded=3, Z is the array whose indexes range within [0..0, 0..N-1].
6317 
6318 Result:
6319  True, if the algorithm has converged.
6320  False, if the algorithm hasn't converged.
6321 
6322  -- LAPACK routine (version 3.0) --
6323  Univ. of Tennessee, Univ. of California Berkeley, NAG Ltd.,
6324  Courant Institute, Argonne National Lab, and Rice University
6325  September 30, 1994
6326 *************************************************************************/
6327 bool smatrixtdevd(real_1d_array &d, const real_1d_array &e, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t zneeded, real_2d_array &z, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6330 /*************************************************************************
6331 Subroutine for finding the tridiagonal matrix eigenvalues/vectors in a
6332 given half-interval (A, B] by using bisection and inverse iteration.
6333 
6334 Input parameters:
6335  D - the main diagonal of a tridiagonal matrix.
6336  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6337  E - the secondary diagonal of a tridiagonal matrix.
6338  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-2].
6339  N - size of matrix, N>=0.
6340  ZNeeded - flag controlling whether the eigenvectors are needed or not.
6341  If ZNeeded is equal to:
6342  * 0, the eigenvectors are not needed;
6343  * 1, the eigenvectors of a tridiagonal matrix are multiplied
6344  by the square matrix Z. It is used if the tridiagonal
6345  matrix is obtained by the similarity transformation
6346  of a symmetric matrix.
6347  * 2, the eigenvectors of a tridiagonal matrix replace matrix Z.
6348  A, B - half-interval (A, B] to search eigenvalues in.
6349  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6350  * 0, Z isn't used and remains unchanged;
6351  * 1, Z contains the square matrix (array whose indexes range
6352  within [0..N-1, 0..N-1]) which reduces the given symmetric
6353  matrix to tridiagonal form;
6354  * 2, Z isn't used (but changed on the exit).
6355 
6356 Output parameters:
6357  D - array of the eigenvalues found.
6358  Array whose index ranges within [0..M-1].
6359  M - number of eigenvalues found in the given half-interval (M>=0).
6360  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6361  * 0, doesn't contain any information;
6362  * 1, contains the product of a given NxN matrix Z (from the
6363  left) and NxM matrix of the eigenvectors found (from the
6364  right). Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..M-1].
6365  * 2, contains the matrix of the eigenvectors found.
6366  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..M-1].
6367 
6368 Result:
6369 
6370  True, if successful. In that case, M contains the number of eigenvalues
6371  in the given half-interval (could be equal to 0), D contains the eigenvalues,
6372  Z contains the eigenvectors (if needed).
6373  It should be noted that the subroutine changes the size of arrays D and Z.
6374 
6375  False, if the bisection method subroutine wasn't able to find the
6376  eigenvalues in the given interval or if the inverse iteration subroutine
6377  wasn't able to find all the corresponding eigenvectors. In that case,
6378  the eigenvalues and eigenvectors are not returned, M is equal to 0.
6379 
6380  -- ALGLIB --
6381  Copyright 31.03.2008 by Bochkanov Sergey

6441 
6442 /*************************************************************************
6443 Finding eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a general (unsymmetric) matrix
6444 
6445  ! COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
6446  !
6447  ! Commercial Edition of ALGLIB includes following important improvements
6448  ! of this function:
6449  ! * high-performance native backend with same C# interface (C# version)
6450  ! * hardware vendor (Intel) implementations of linear algebra primitives
6451  ! (C++ and C# versions, x86/x64 platform)
6452  !
6453  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
6454  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
6455  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
6456 
6457 The algorithm finds eigenvalues and eigenvectors of a general matrix by
6458 using the QR algorithm with multiple shifts. The algorithm can find
6459 eigenvalues and both left and right eigenvectors.
6460 
6461 The right eigenvector is a vector x such that A*x = w*x, and the left
6462 eigenvector is a vector y such that y'*A = w*y' (here y' implies a complex
6463 conjugate transposition of vector y).
6464 
6465 Input parameters:
6466  A - matrix. Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6467  N - size of matrix A.
6468  VNeeded - flag controlling whether eigenvectors are needed or not.
6469  If VNeeded is equal to:
6470  * 0, eigenvectors are not returned;
6471  * 1, right eigenvectors are returned;
6472  * 2, left eigenvectors are returned;
6473  * 3, both left and right eigenvectors are returned.
6474 
6475 Output parameters:
6476  WR - real parts of eigenvalues.
6477  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6478  WR - imaginary parts of eigenvalues.
6479  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6480  VL, VR - arrays of left and right eigenvectors (if they are needed).
6481  If WI[i]=0, the respective eigenvalue is a real number,
6482  and it corresponds to the column number I of matrices VL/VR.
6483  If WI[i]>0, we have a pair of complex conjugate numbers with
6484  positive and negative imaginary parts:
6485  the first eigenvalue WR[i] + sqrt(-1)*WI[i];
6486  the second eigenvalue WR[i+1] + sqrt(-1)*WI[i+1];
6487  WI[i]>0
6488  WI[i+1] = -WI[i] < 0
6489  In that case, the eigenvector corresponding to the first
6490  eigenvalue is located in i and i+1 columns of matrices
6491  VL/VR (the column number i contains the real part, and the
6492  column number i+1 contains the imaginary part), and the vector
6493  corresponding to the second eigenvalue is a complex conjugate to
6494  the first vector.
6495  Arrays whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6496 
6497 Result:
6498  True, if the algorithm has converged.
6499  False, if the algorithm has not converged.
6500 
6501 Note 1:
6502  Some users may ask the following question: what if WI[N-1]>0?
6503  WI[N] must contain an eigenvalue which is complex conjugate to the
6504  N-th eigenvalue, but the array has only size N?
6505  The answer is as follows: such a situation cannot occur because the
6506  algorithm finds a pairs of eigenvalues, therefore, if WI[i]>0, I is
6507  strictly less than N-1.
6508 
6509 Note 2:
6510  The algorithm performance depends on the value of the internal parameter
6511  NS of the InternalSchurDecomposition subroutine which defines the number
6512  of shifts in the QR algorithm (similarly to the block width in block-matrix
6513  algorithms of linear algebra). If you require maximum performance
6514  on your machine, it is recommended to adjust this parameter manually.
6515 
6516 
6517 See also the InternalTREVC subroutine.
6518 
6519 The algorithm is based on the LAPACK 3.0 library.
6520 *************************************************************************/
6521 bool rmatrixevd(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t vneeded, real_1d_array &wr, real_1d_array &wi, real_2d_array &vl, real_2d_array &vr, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6522 #endif
6523 
6524 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_SCHUR) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
6525 /*************************************************************************
6526 Subroutine performing the Schur decomposition of a general matrix by using
6527 the QR algorithm with multiple shifts.
6528 
6529 COMMERCIAL EDITION OF ALGLIB:
6530 
6531  ! Commercial version of ALGLIB includes one important improvement of
6532  ! this function, which can be used from C++ and C#:
6533  ! * Intel MKL support (lightweight Intel MKL is shipped with ALGLIB)
6534  !
6535  ! Intel MKL gives approximately constant (with respect to number of
6536  ! worker threads) acceleration factor which depends on CPU being used,
6537  ! problem size and "baseline" ALGLIB edition which is used for
6538  ! comparison.
6539  !
6540  ! Multithreaded acceleration is NOT supported for this function.
6541  !
6542  ! We recommend you to read 'Working with commercial version' section of
6543  ! ALGLIB Reference Manual in order to find out how to use performance-
6544  ! related features provided by commercial edition of ALGLIB.
6545 
6546 The source matrix A is represented as S'*A*S = T, where S is an orthogonal
6547 matrix (Schur vectors), T - upper quasi-triangular matrix (with blocks of
6548 sizes 1x1 and 2x2 on the main diagonal).
6549 
6550 Input parameters:
6551  A - matrix to be decomposed.
6552  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6553  N - size of A, N>=0.
6554 
6555 
6556 Output parameters:
6557  A - contains matrix T.
6558  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6559  S - contains Schur vectors.
6560  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6561 
6562 Note 1:
6563  The block structure of matrix T can be easily recognized: since all
6564  the elements below the blocks are zeros, the elements a[i+1,i] which
6565  are equal to 0 show the block border.
6566 
6567 Note 2:
6568  The algorithm performance depends on the value of the internal parameter
6569  NS of the InternalSchurDecomposition subroutine which defines the number
6570  of shifts in the QR algorithm (similarly to the block width in block-matrix
6571  algorithms in linear algebra). If you require maximum performance on
6572  your machine, it is recommended to adjust this parameter manually.
6573 
6574 Result:
6575  True,
6576  if the algorithm has converged and parameters A and S contain the result.
6577  False,
6578  if the algorithm has not converged.
6579 
6580 Algorithm implemented on the basis of the DHSEQR subroutine (LAPACK 3.0 library).
6581 *************************************************************************/
6582 bool rmatrixschur(real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, real_2d_array &s, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6583 #endif
6584 
6585 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_SPDGEVD) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
6586 /*************************************************************************
6587 Algorithm for solving the following generalized symmetric positive-definite
6588 eigenproblem:
6589  A*x = lambda*B*x (1) or
6590  A*B*x = lambda*x (2) or
6591  B*A*x = lambda*x (3).
6592 where A is a symmetric matrix, B - symmetric positive-definite matrix.
6593 The problem is solved by reducing it to an ordinary symmetric eigenvalue
6594 problem.
6595 
6596 Input parameters:
6597  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
6598  triangular part.
6599  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6600  N - size of matrices A and B.
6601  IsUpperA - storage format of matrix A.
6602  B - symmetric positive-definite matrix which is given by
6603  its upper or lower triangular part.
6604  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6605  IsUpperB - storage format of matrix B.
6606  ZNeeded - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6607  * 0, the eigenvectors are not returned;
6608  * 1, the eigenvectors are returned.
6609  ProblemType - if ProblemType is equal to:
6610  * 1, the following problem is solved: A*x = lambda*B*x;
6611  * 2, the following problem is solved: A*B*x = lambda*x;
6612  * 3, the following problem is solved: B*A*x = lambda*x.
6613 
6614 Output parameters:
6615  D - eigenvalues in ascending order.
6616  Array whose index ranges within [0..N-1].
6617  Z - if ZNeeded is equal to:
6618  * 0, Z hasn't changed;
6619  * 1, Z contains eigenvectors.
6620  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6621  The eigenvectors are stored in matrix columns. It should
6622  be noted that the eigenvectors in such problems do not
6623  form an orthogonal system.
6624 
6625 Result:
6626  True, if the problem was solved successfully.
6627  False, if the error occurred during the Cholesky decomposition of matrix
6628  B (the matrix isn't positive-definite) or during the work of the iterative
6629  algorithm for solving the symmetric eigenproblem.
6630 
6631 See also the GeneralizedSymmetricDefiniteEVDReduce subroutine.
6632 
6633  -- ALGLIB --
6634  Copyright 1.28.2006 by Bochkanov Sergey
6635 *************************************************************************/
6636 bool smatrixgevd(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isuppera, const real_2d_array &b, const bool isupperb, const ae_int_t zneeded, const ae_int_t problemtype, real_1d_array &d, real_2d_array &z, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6638 
6639 /*************************************************************************
6640 Algorithm for reduction of the following generalized symmetric positive-
6641 definite eigenvalue problem:
6642  A*x = lambda*B*x (1) or
6643  A*B*x = lambda*x (2) or
6644  B*A*x = lambda*x (3)
6645 to the symmetric eigenvalues problem C*y = lambda*y (eigenvalues of this and
6646 the given problems are the same, and the eigenvectors of the given problem
6647 could be obtained by multiplying the obtained eigenvectors by the
6648 transformation matrix x = R*y).
6649 
6650 Here A is a symmetric matrix, B - symmetric positive-definite matrix.
6651 
6652 Input parameters:
6653  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
6654  triangular part.
6655  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6656  N - size of matrices A and B.
6657  IsUpperA - storage format of matrix A.
6658  B - symmetric positive-definite matrix which is given by
6659  its upper or lower triangular part.
6660  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6661  IsUpperB - storage format of matrix B.
6662  ProblemType - if ProblemType is equal to:
6663  * 1, the following problem is solved: A*x = lambda*B*x;
6664  * 2, the following problem is solved: A*B*x = lambda*x;
6665  * 3, the following problem is solved: B*A*x = lambda*x.
6666 
6667 Output parameters:
6668  A - symmetric matrix which is given by its upper or lower
6669  triangle depending on IsUpperA. Contains matrix C.
6670  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6671  R - upper triangular or low triangular transformation matrix
6672  which is used to obtain the eigenvectors of a given problem
6673  as the product of eigenvectors of C (from the right) and
6674  matrix R (from the left). If the matrix is upper
6675  triangular, the elements below the main diagonal
6676  are equal to 0 (and vice versa). Thus, we can perform
6677  the multiplication without taking into account the
6678  internal structure (which is an easier though less
6679  effective way).
6680  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6681  IsUpperR - type of matrix R (upper or lower triangular).
6682 
6683 Result:
6684  True, if the problem was reduced successfully.
6685  False, if the error occurred during the Cholesky decomposition of
6686  matrix B (the matrix is not positive-definite).
6687 
6688  -- ALGLIB --
6689  Copyright 1.28.2006 by Bochkanov Sergey
6690 *************************************************************************/
6691 bool smatrixgevdreduce(real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isuppera, const real_2d_array &b, const bool isupperb, const ae_int_t problemtype, real_2d_array &r, bool &isupperr, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6692 #endif
6693 
6694 #if defined(AE_COMPILE_INVERSEUPDATE) || !defined(AE_PARTIAL_BUILD)
6695 /*************************************************************************
6696 Inverse matrix update by the Sherman-Morrison formula
6697 
6698 The algorithm updates matrix A^-1 when adding a number to an element
6699 of matrix A.
6700 
6701 Input parameters:
6702  InvA - inverse of matrix A.
6703  Array whose indexes range within [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6704  N - size of matrix A.
6705  UpdRow - row where the element to be updated is stored.
6706  UpdColumn - column where the element to be updated is stored.
6707  UpdVal - a number to be added to the element.
6708 
6709 
6710 Output parameters:
6711  InvA - inverse of modified matrix A.
6712 
6713  -- ALGLIB --
6714  Copyright 2005 by Bochkanov Sergey
6715 *************************************************************************/
6716 void rmatrixinvupdatesimple(real_2d_array &inva, const ae_int_t n, const ae_int_t updrow, const ae_int_t updcolumn, const double updval, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6880 /*************************************************************************
6881 Determinant calculation of the matrix given by the Cholesky decomposition.
6882 
6883 Input parameters:
6884  A - Cholesky decomposition,
6885  output of SMatrixCholesky subroutine.
6886  N - (optional) size of matrix A:
6887  * if given, only principal NxN submatrix is processed and
6888  overwritten. other elements are unchanged.
6889  * if not given, automatically determined from matrix size
6890  (A must be square matrix)
6891 
6892 As the determinant is equal to the product of squares of diagonal elements,
6893 it's not necessary to specify which triangle - lower or upper - the matrix
6894 is stored in.
6895 
6896 Result:
6897  matrix determinant.
6898 
6899  -- ALGLIB --
6900  Copyright 2005-2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
6901 *************************************************************************/
6902 double spdmatrixcholeskydet(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);

6905 
6906 /*************************************************************************
6907 Determinant calculation of the symmetric positive definite matrix.
6908 
6909 Input parameters:
6910  A - matrix. Array with elements [0..N-1, 0..N-1].
6911  N - (optional) size of matrix A:
6912  * if given, only principal NxN submatrix is processed and
6913  overwritten. other elements are unchanged.
6914  * if not given, automatically determined from matrix size
6915  (A must be square matrix)
6916  IsUpper - (optional) storage type:
6917  * if True, symmetric matrix A is given by its upper
6918  triangle, and the lower triangle isn't used/changed by
6919  function
6920  * if False, symmetric matrix A is given by its lower
6921  triangle, and the upper triangle isn't used/changed by
6922  function
6923  * if not given, both lower and upper triangles must be
6924  filled.
6925 
6926 Result:
6927  determinant of matrix A.
6928  If matrix A is not positive definite, exception is thrown.
6929 
6930  -- ALGLIB --
6931  Copyright 2005-2008 by Bochkanov Sergey
6932 *************************************************************************/
6933 double spdmatrixdet(const real_2d_array &a, const ae_int_t n, const bool isupper, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
6934 double spdmatrixdet(const real_2d_array &a, const xparams _xparams = alglib::xdefault);
